Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim the @butternut squash{1}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the seeds (peel 
first if you prefer). Cut widthways into 1cm thick slices.

Pop the butternut onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{1/2%tbsp} and 
half the @harissa paste{50%g}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, 
then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. 
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat the oil (see pantry for amount) in a deep #saucepan{} on medium heat. Once 
hot, add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g} and cook until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water{240%ml} for the bulgur, stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} 
and bring to the boil. Simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan and 
remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, cut the @tomato{2%medium} into 2cm chunks.

Pick the @mint{1}(picked, leaves only) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop 
(discard the stalks). Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}.

Crumble the @Greek style salad cheese{100%g}(crumbled) into small pieces.

Once the bulgur is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{}.

Gently stir in the tomatoes, lemon zest, remaining harissa paste (use less if 
you'd prefer things milder), half the mint and half the Greek style salad 
cheese.

Squeeze in some lemon juice, then taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} 
if needed.

When everything's ready, share the tabbouleh between your #bowls{} and top with 
the roasted butternut squash.

Scatter over the @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} and remaining Greek style salad 
cheese, then top with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}.

Sprinkle with the remaining mint to finish. Enjoy!